  "body": "When testing Crowdsale functionalities, we usually have an `investor` account that represents an account that will be receiving the tokens when they are bought, e.g.:\r\n\r\n```\r\nit('should assign tokens to sender', async function () {\r\n   await this.crowdsale.sendTransaction({ value: value, from: investor });\r\n   (await this.token.balanceOf(investor)).should.be.bignumber.equal(expectedTokenAmount);\r\n});\r\n```\r\n\r\nGiven the current regulatory uncertainties and the thin line that sometimes exists between security and utility tokens, I think many projects have gone wary of using the word investor in any of their conversation and written material describing their project. Code should be no exception (even in tests),  and I believe it would thus make sense to rename `investor` to something else such as `participant`.\r\n\r\nNote that we also have the `purchaser` account, which is then one providing the funds to buy tokens for the participant in the case of a low-level purchase.\r\n\r\nThis issue could likely be fixed together with issue #1357 that also aims to change a name in the tests.",
